iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cairo - Egypt's central bank says that inflation fell to 29.7% in May, down from 31.5% in April, the first decline in seven months when the Egyptian pound was devalued.The figures, published by the CBE Thursday, also show that year-on-year core inflation declined to 30.5% in May, down from 32.1% in April. Core inflation excludes volatile commodities such as food and energy.Egypt floated its currency in November to meet a key demand set by the International Monetary Fund in exchange for a $12bn loan to support the country's ailing economy. An installment of $2.75bn has already been paid out, while another $1.2bn installment has met preliminary approval.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.